# Branch Finishing / PR Prep

## Iron Law
`NEVER MERGE WITHOUT ALL CHECKS PASSING`

---

## Steps

### 1. Verify
Confirm the branch is ready for review.

- Run the full test suite -- all tests must pass
- Run typecheck and linting -- zero errors
- Verify all acceptance criteria from the story/PRD are met
- Check that no debug code, console.logs, or TODO hacks remain
- Confirm no untracked files that should be committed

```bash
git status
# Run project-specific quality checks
```

### 2. Rebase
Bring the branch up to date with the target branch.

```bash
git fetch origin
git rebase origin/main
```

- Resolve any conflicts carefully -- do not blindly accept
- After rebase, re-run all quality checks (rebase can introduce subtle breakage)
- If conflicts are complex, consider merging instead of rebasing

### 3. Clean History
Make the commit history tell a clear story.

- Each commit should represent one logical change
- Commit messages should explain WHY, not just WHAT
- Remove fixup commits, WIP commits, and "oops" commits
- Ensure no commits include unrelated changes

```bash
git log --oneline origin/main..HEAD
```

### 4. Write PR Description
Create a clear, complete pull request description.

Structure:
- **Title**: Short, descriptive (under 70 characters)
- **Summary**: 1-3 bullet points explaining what changed and why
- **Test plan**: How to verify the changes work
- **Breaking changes**: Note any breaking changes explicitly
- **Screenshots**: Include if there are UI changes

### 5. Self-Review
Review your own diff before requesting review from others.

```bash
git diff origin/main...HEAD
```

Check for:
- Accidental file inclusions (.env, credentials, large binaries)
- Code that does not match the PR description
- Missing error handling or edge cases
- Inconsistent naming or style

### 6. Push and Create PR

```bash
git push origin <branch-name> -u
gh pr create --title "<title>" --body "<description>"
```

- Verify the PR was created successfully
- Assign reviewers if applicable
- Link to related issues or stories

---

## Red Flags

| Thought | Reality |
|---|---|
| "Tests mostly pass, close enough" | ALL checks must pass. No exceptions. |
| "I'll fix that in a follow-up PR" | Fix it now. Follow-up PRs get forgotten. |
| "The diff is too big to self-review" | If the diff is too big to review, it is too big to merge. Split it. |
| "Rebasing is too risky, I'll just merge" | Rebase when possible for clean history. Only merge if conflicts are genuinely complex. |
| "Nobody reads PR descriptions" | Your future self reads them. Your reviewers read them. Write them well. |

---

## Rules

- NEVER merge without all checks passing
- NEVER skip self-review
- ALWAYS rebase onto the latest target branch before pushing
- ALWAYS write a meaningful PR description
- Keep PRs focused -- one feature or fix per PR
